            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>RS: I think the public option basically is a good idea in the sense that, for selected individuals that can&rsquo;t get private insurance in other ways, there is an opportunity to be a bit more experimental in designing better, more cost-effective models of care. So on that side, I like it. The danger of a public option, if it&rsquo;s not done right, is that the government pays for care at a much lower rate than private insurance. And most physicians and hospitals will tell you that they could not exist solely on the government rate. So by having a public option, there really is an unlevel playing field in the sense that the public option-type insurance has the benefit of lower expenses than private insurers. That&rsquo;s a complicated answer, but unfortunately it is the reality, which makes the public option a difficult concept, although basically I think it is a good concept.</p>
<p>TC: There are many problems in our current system that are too pervasive to be fixed with one law or can even be adequately addressed by one push for reform.&nbsp; How do you see our health care system changing and our efforts at reform evolving as we move into the future?</p>
<p>RS: I think that the most important initiative that could come from the health care legislation itself would be to change how medical costs are reimbursed to the providers&mdash;in other words, the reimbursement system which currently rewards disease rather than prevention. I think that would be the most important thing. I have to say there is a second thing, which is absolutely essential, and that is that individuals&mdash;you, me, and everyone else who reads this article&mdash;understands that health is one of their greatest resources, and they need to take ownership of it. What individuals can do for themselves, for most of their lives, is at least as great as what the health system can do for them. As a country, we need to understand the importance of our own health, and I am proud that Duke has developed a Prospective Health Care Club among its own students that truly values the importance of health.</p>

